<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / International Company News: Svenska Handelsbanken recovers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Svenska Handelsbanken underscored the momentum of its recovery from the
Swedish banking crisis yesterday by announcing a near four-fold rise in
profits for the first quarter.
The bank achieved an operating profit of SKr1.23bn (Dollars 155m), compared
with a SKr316m surplus in the same period in 1993.
The improvement was entirely due to a 54 per cent cut in credit losses to
SKr839m from SKr1.82bn.
Before credit losses the result was marginally worse - a SKr2.07bn profit
compared with SKr2.14bn - reflecting subdued lending levels and tighter
margins. Overall income fell 1 per cent to SKr3.47bn from SKr3.51bn.
Handelsbanken said credit losses now accounted for just 1.2 per cent of
total lending, half the level a year ago. It also said problem credits had
fallen sharply to SKr8.48bn at the end of the quarter compared with
SKr13.7bn at the end of March 1993. At the end of 1993 problem credits were
SKr9.70bn.
The bank's capital adequacy ratio strengthened to 13.1 per cent at the end
of the quarter, against 12.9 per cent at the end of 1993.
</TEXT>
