<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / UK Company News: Thonet range to sit alongside Parker Knoll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Parker Knoll, famous for its reclining chairs, has announced that it is to
distribute in the UK and the Irish Republic the modern chairs of Thonet of
Austria, linking two of the world's most famous names in furniture.
Michael Thonet, the inventor of the process by which wood for furniture is
steamed and bent, brought his chairs to London for the Great Exhibition in
1851, finding international success and sales.
Thonet, who had won the backing of Prince Metternich, the Austrian
chancellor, had five sons who continued to spread the company's products
around the globe. Between 1880 and 1930, when it employed more than 10,000
workers, the company made 50m chairs.
Martin and Tom Jourdan, descendants of Frederick Parker, who founded Parker
Knoll in 1870, walked into the Cologne furniture fair 14 months ago and
offered to distribute Thonet's modern designs in the UK, alongside the
Parker Knoll range, part of the furniture division of Cornwell Parker.
The joint venture was announced in the Victoria and Albert Museum, where two
of Michael Thonet's chairs are on permanent display.
</TEXT>
