<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Santander wins control of Banesto
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Banco Santander last night outbid its rivals to win control of Banco Espanol
de Credito and create Spain's largest banking group.
It will pay Pta281bn (Pounds 1.38bn) for a 60 per cent stake in the bank
following a rescue operation conducted under the auspices of the Bank of
Spain.
In an atmosphere of acute suspense, the verdict was announced four and a
half hours after the opening of sealed bids from three competing banks. The
other bidders were Banco Bilbao Vizcaya and the state-controlled Argentaria.
The winning bid of Pta762 per share was well above most analysts' forecasts
and slightly higher than Banesto's closing share price yesterday of Pta755.
Santander said yesterday it planned to retain Mr Alfredo Saenz, the
caretaker Banesto chairman.
The Bank of Spain, which stepped into Banesto four months ago and sacked its
management board, opted for a rapid decision to help rebuild confidence
after the country's largest ever bank crisis.
Banesto is estimated to have lost Pta350bn in deposits - nearly 15 per cent
 -following the intervention in December.
Santander said its strategy for Banesto would centre on its retail banking
strength and giving it 'an exclusively financial vocation'. This suggested
that it planned to dispose of Banesto's extensive portfolio of industrial
holdings.
The bids from BBV and Argentaria came in below Santander's at Pta667 and
Pta566 respectively. The contest, judged by an eight-member panel chaired by
the Bank of Spain, was held solely on the basis of price.
</TEXT>
