<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / ABF held to Pounds 181m by fall in gilt market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 28m drop in investment income at Associated British Foods to Pounds
17m following the fall in the gilt-edged market held interim pre-tax profits
growth to Pounds 5m, up to Pounds 181m, at the bread, flour, biscuits and
sugar group.
Interest charges fell from Pounds 15m to Pounds 13m. The pre-tax profit
included a Pounds 29m gain on the group's investment in Berisford
International, which compared with a Pounds 15m gain in 1993. Without that
gain profits would have been Pounds 9m lower and the share price fell 15p to
583p.
Mr Garry Weston, chairman, said the group's cash pile should be transferred
into 'something capable of long-term returns greater than from gilts'.
AB Foods last week announced a Pounds 35m acquisition of J Bibby &amp; Sons'
agricultural business and Mr Weston said there could be more such deals. He
said it was the sort of acquisition which 'pays off quickly' whereas a
number of food companies on offer were expensive.
Capital expenditure was Pounds 90m, while depreciation was Pounds 79m, and
would exceed Pounds 200m for the year, he said. Even so, without a large
acquisition in the second half, cash should be higher at the year end than
the Pounds 501m in last September's balance sheet, he said.
At the half-year end net cash stood at Pounds 356m, against Pounds 283m at
the same time in 1993. During the first half AB Foods runs down its cash as
it builds up sugar and wheat stocks after harvest.
Operating profits in the 24 weeks to March 5 were 13.1 per cent ahead at
Pounds 147m, up from Pounds 130m, on sales only 1 per cent higher at Pounds
2.06bn. Much of the gain came from higher productivity and greater
efficiencies, Mr Weston said, including 1,200 job losses in the bakery
division.
Pressure from retailers was fierce with supermarket customers getting 'a
little bit more bad-tempered', he said. Discounts on bread prices had
increased by 3 1/2 per cent over the year, on a business with sales of
Pounds 700m.
Operating profits from manufacturing rose from Pounds 117m to Pounds 125m,
including a Pounds 2m rise at British Sugar to Pounds 77m. British Sugar
continued heavy investment. The Kings Lynn plant is closing while that at
Wissington is doubling in size.
Milling and baking profits together were ahead, and higher exports increased
profits from biscuits and Twinings tea. Profits from Australia and New
Zealand fell Pounds 1m to Pounds 16m as fierce bread price wars raged there.
Retailing, largely in Ireland, improved profits from Pounds 13m to Pounds
22m as the price wars of the first half of 1993 had abated.
Earnings per share were 4.8 per cent higher at 28.5p. The interim dividend
is unchanged at 8.5p, and Mr Weston said any increase for the year would be
reflected in the second payment.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
