<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / The Lex Column: Deutsche Bank
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Embarrassing though the Schneider affair is for Deutsche Bank, it is
difficult to justify any serious impact on its share price. Yesterday the
bank admitted the need for a few hundred million D-Marks in provisions. But
provisions in 1993 were DM3.3bn and Deutsche warned in its final results
statement that they would again be high this year. The Schneider failure
does not materially alter expectations. Nor does it appear to signal a
general deterioration of property market conditions which might engender
further bankruptcies.
Harder to quantify is the effect on the bank's image. There have been
striking lapses of management in both the Schneider and the
Metallgesellschaft cases. It will be awkward for Deutsche if either problem
necessitates resignations at a senior level. Yet here again it is difficult
to see financial implications. Arguably Deutsche's tarnished image might
accelerate its disengagement from industry so that it would eventually face
more competition in its home market. But that is a long term process and one
that was already under way.
There is thus every chance that Deutsche's shares will make up more of the
ground lost since the Schneider affair broke. Whether they can manage a
period of sustained out-performance is another matter, given the market's
predilection for cyclical industrial stocks over interest-sensitive
financials. That is a much weightier matter now the recovery looms and
interest rates approach their floor.
</TEXT>
