<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / The Lex Column: ABF
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The strong rise in Associated British Foods' shares this year was prompted
by hopes it might mobilise its chronically under-geared balance sheet and
buy something big. With some Pounds 2bn of shareholders' funds and Pounds
356m of net cash, Mr Garry Weston certainly has plenty of dough to play
with. But ABF remained quiet about any such intentions yesterday as Mr
Weston kept playing his famously long game. So the market chose to fret
instead about the continuing stodginess of ABF's milling and baking
activities. One day ABF will generate a decent return on its Pounds 400m of
assets in that area. But many suns will set before that day arrives. At
least, the recovery in Irish retailing is providing some encouragement,
while British Sugar is still proving its worth.
Most of the moving parts at ABF are therefore at the margin. ABF took a
Pounds 29m profit from writing up the value of its investment in Berisford
and selling some of its nil-paid rights. But that was offset by the slump in
investment income from Pounds 45m to Pounds 17m. The previous year's numbers
were flattered by the exceptional markets which followed the pound's removal
from the ERM. Even so, the returns ABF is currently generating on its cash
balances look none too clever. ABF incurred some capital losses in the bond
market. It would have got a better return leaving its money on deposit in
the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester. Given the importance of investment income to
group profits, ABF should disclose where it now intends to puts its money.
</TEXT>
