<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
John Betjeman was great television so there are high hopes for an Omnibus
profile (BBC 1, 10.55) of this tortured but likeable man, who moved from
revolutionary to diehard with charm and aplomb. His reputation has risen
since his death and there are enough friends and enemies around to cast
insights on his life.
This is preceded by 'The Riff Raff Element', one of my favourite programmes
of 1993 and given a reassuringly swift return in this new series. The
Belchers are common; the Tundishes are gentry, and their lives have somehow
intermeshed. But no cheap points are scored and all the characters have
their own quirky individuality.
Coal (BBC2, 9.50) is another report on the death of the mining industry,
this time with the added poignancy that Charles Stewart and Malcolm Hirst
have taken their fly-on the-wall approach to the pits in Nottinghamshire,
the recruiting ground for the Union of Democratic Miners, which helped the
government break the miners strike of 1984 but which now faces the closure
of its own pits. The first of six episodes in a sorry tale.
</TEXT>
