<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Condemned to print in 'Scabland': Staff in Bristol, still
picketing after a year, talk to Roland Adburgham
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A placard outside the gates at printing company JW Arrowsmith reads: 'You
don't have to visit Scabland.'
The family-owned Bristol business has been picketed since the 121 workers
were sacked for taking industrial action over a national pay claim a year
ago today. At the same time, the company derecognised the GPMU printing
union.
A rally marking the anniversary will be held on Saturday. Mr Geoff Collard,
branch secretary of the GPMU, said: 'I believe it is the longest running
industrial dispute in the history of Bristol. We are hoping to make the
rally the biggest show of solidarity of trade unionists this city has ever
seen.'
Labour politicians such as Mr Ian White, MEP for Bristol, see the case as
highlighting the weakness of UK employment law for workers. The company
argues that it acted fairly.
Mr Tony Burke, GPMU deputy general secretary, praises the 'remarkable'
solidarity of the union's members at Arrowsmith and at two smaller
long-running disputes - Revell &amp; George in Manchester and Harvest Printers
in Macclesfield, Cheshire. He believes the disputes have been significant in
persuading other printing firms to return to a national pay agreement.
Mr Burke said union members had voted last week to accept a 2.8 per cent
national pay offer for 1994 and the British Printing Industry Federation had
agreed to use its 'good offices' to try to resolve the three disputes.
Arrowsmith, with a national reputation for technical typesetting, had a
long-serving and non-militant workforce. Now there is acrimony. 'I know
there is no chance of getting my job back,' Mr Dave Rose, who had been with
Arrowsmith for 15 years, remarked as he warmed himself beside a brazier.
'But if they get away with this, other employers will do the same. It is a
fight for union rights.'
Mr Paul Samphier, dismissed after 26 years, said he was living on Pounds 60
a week dispute benefit from the union and Pounds 40 unemployment pay. 'I had
been earning just over Pounds 300 a week.' Eighty-two staff are still out of
work, according to the unon, although it will not disclose how much the
dispute is costing it.
Arrowsmith has suffered as well. The dispute began when losses of Pounds
210,000 in 1992 caused it to resist last year's pay claim of an extra Pounds
6.50 a week. Printers started an unofficial overtime ban and, after they
voted for a strike, the company dismissed them for breach of contract.
It offered to take people back at the old pay rates and without recognition
of the union. Only six returned. Union members lost a subsequent claim for
unfair dismissal. Arrowsmith's workforce has been more than halved to 65 and
losses last year escalated to Pounds 670,000.
The union accuses Miss Victoria Arrowsmith-Brown, the company's head, of
having intended to reduce the workforce and of using the industrial action
as a means to avoid redundancy payments. Mr Collard said: 'We are still
seeking to reach a sensible negotiated settlement - but she's turned her
back on every overture.'
Miss Arrowsmith-Brown has argued that the company was damaged by the
overtime disruption, and that its reduction in size was not a preconceived
strategy.
Mr James Arrowsmith-Brown, her brother and the company's finance director,
said: 'The dispute is completely dead as far as we're concerned. 'There is
no question of recognition - we made that decision after the people were
dismissed. Everything we have seen since has pushed us further and further
away from recognition.'
Arrowsmith has had to cut back on typesetting but Mr Arrowsmith-Brown is
confident it will survive. He has budgeted for a nominal profit this year.
The company wants to sell its 3.2-acre freehold site, move to smaller
premises and buy a new printing press.
He describes the past year as 'a complete disaster - no one would ever want
to see it again. One can argue about the rights and wrongs for years to
come, but we believe we were right. But one is never proud of any
participation in 120 people being put out of work.'
</TEXT>
