<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Doubt cast on methane estimates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK emitted around 5m tonnes of methane in 1990 as a result of human
activity, but estimates remain highly uncertain, a government report said
yesterday, Bronwen Maddox writes.
Methane is the second most important gas - after carbon dioxide - which is
emitted by human activity and which could contribute to global warming. It
is generated by rotting or burning organic matter including fossil fuels
such as oil, gas and coal.
The UK programme for limiting emissions of gases which could cause climate
change, published in January, set out plans to cut methane emissions
resulting from people's activities by 5 per cent on 1990 levels by the year
2000.
Methane Emissions Inventory. NPL, Teddington, Middlesex, TW11 0LW.
</TEXT>
