<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Newton and Gartmore top fund manager list
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Newton and Gartmore are the two best-performing managers of UK pension funds
over five years according to this year's performance league table compiled
by the Financial Times.
Newton was also the leader on a one-year view, reporting a median return of
37.4 per cent, followed by M &amp; G with 34.0 per cent. The median return for
managers as a whole was 29.2 per cent, according to the performance
measurement firm Caps.
Phillips &amp; Drew Fund Management, second a year ago, has slipped to fourth
after an indifferent 1993 in which it suffered by anticipating a stock
market downturn too early. However, in the first quarter of 1994 it has
gained 2.2 per cent compared with the estimated Caps median, which was minus
4.6 per cent.
The figures for the house median rate of return have been supplied by the
managers and calculated in accordance with the National Association of
Pension Funds Code. However several managers, including industry leader
Mercury Asset Management, did not provide information.
The performance figures are regarded in some quarters as controversial,
because they are subject to a degree of cosmetic adjustment and because they
obscure differences between individual client funds.
'Half of our clients are below our in-house average, so 50 per cent will be
unhappy if the figure is published,' says one new business director. 'That
is a slightly silly position to be in.'
This is generally thought to be a particular problem for MAM, which had 442
clients at the end of last year. Big managers such as MAM offer a broader
range of products, and the concept of a standard discretionary management
strategy is difficult to apply.
Nevertheless, performance over the short to medium term is still the most
powerful factor driving new business. The biggest gainers of new client
money last year were PDFM, Schroder and Gartmore, all of which are leaders
in the five-year table.
Two smaller managers, Newton and Baillie Gifford, raised their pension fund
assets under management by 60 per cent last year, in spite of being closed
to new clients at various times.
To beat the median last year in UK equities, managers needed to be heavily
exposed to cyclical recovery stocks - a characteristic style of M &amp; G, for
instance - and light in formerly highly rated growth sectors such as
pharmaceuticals and food retailing. Small company shares outperformed the
big blue chips.
Overseas, the US was relatively weak and Japan neutral, so funds did well to
be heavily invested in continental Europe and especially in south-east Asia
and emerging markets.
Property was a drag compared to the sparkling performance of global
equities. But fund managers have needed to perform some rapid U-turns this
year. Property has been the best asset to hold so far, and unless managers
have quickly got out of Hong Kong and the emerging markets they could be at
the bottom of the 1994 performance league.
