<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Bosses urged to help fight asthma
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies were urged yesterday to give employees better protection against
asthma-causing chemicals after a report disclosed that 1,000 asthma cases a
year are developed in the workplace.
The warning was issued by the Health and Safety Executive, which has
launched an education campaign aimed mainly at small and medium-sized
businesses.
Dr Tim Carter, HSE director of field operations and medical services, said
some 200 asthma - inducing substances had been identified, ranging from
isocyanates, found in paints, to grain dust.
Industries where such substances were used included agriculture, food
manufacture, electronics, metal manufacturing and treatment, plastics
processing, chemical processing and woodworking.
'Some sufferers are so disabled by the illness that they cannot work, and
most have to change jobs to avoid re-exposure,' he said.
</TEXT>
