<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Night flights threaten to stall BAe airport plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The application by British Aerospace for a commercial airport at Filton,
Bristol, is being recommended for rejection unless BAe abandons proposals
for night-time flying, Roland Adburgham writes.
BAe's plans are due to be considered by councillors at the local planning
authority, Northavon, tomorrow. The company wants to have scheduled services
for up to 350,000 passengers a year from its existing airfield at Filton and
up to 20 freight movements a night. But there is vociferous opposition from
local residents.
Northavon planning officers, after a year's consideration of BAe's
application, say the councillors should tomorrow defer a decision to allow
BAe to consider dropping night-time flying. They say night flights are
unacceptable because of the large number of houses which would be affected
by noise. The officers also want more negotiations with BAe on other
restrictions and would like to consider a joint meeting with Bristol city
council and Avon county council, which both want a public inquiry.
BAe wants to make more use of its Filton runway to help to safeguard the
future of its Filton works, where it employs 5,000 people. It said yesterday
Northavon's consultants had calculated that 1,300 houses could be affected
by night-time noise, whereas its own consultants put the figure at 130.
The company said it believed its figures could be validated. It said
Northavon's consultants had based the noise contour on Gatwick airport
statistics where, because of a longer runway, aircraft could have a heavier
take-off weight which increased noise.
</TEXT>
