<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Speedy set-up of Channel 5 in balance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Officials from the Department of National Heritage and the Department of
Trade and Industry will meet today to try to finalise their position on
whether a new Channel 5 that uses existing technology should be given the
go-ahead.
The issue is due to be raised in cabinet this week but a final decision is
not expected.
The Independent Television Commission wants to advertise Channel 5 and has
asked whether the frequencies are still available. The DTI has been studying
the implications of the launch of Channel 5 on the development of digital
terrestrial television.
At the moment the outcome seems evenly balanced between the immediate
benefits of a channel available to 70 per cent of the population and the
preservation of the maximum potential for launching digital television.
Mr Peter Brooke, the national heritage secretary, has not yet received the
report of the Radio Regulatory Agency on the issue.
Meanwhile a study commissioned by the two largest ITV groups, Carlton and
Granada, was last night delivered to the government.
The discussion document, produced by Spectrum Strategy, argues strongly in
favour of the long-term desirability of digital terrestrial transmission. It
says all the potentially available frequencies should be reserved for this
purpose.
The study says the long-term gains include: more efficient use of scarce
frequencies; the continuation of a universally available service with
broader channel choice; and a clear path for the introduction of
high-definition television.
Spectrum concludes that the advantages Channel 5 offers - an immediate
extension of choice for viewers and greater competition for advertisers  -
are outweighed by the advantages of digital transmission, even though
digital could only be funded by national subscription channels.
</TEXT>
