<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Exports to Malaysia up despite row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British exports to Malaysia rose slightly last month despite the
anti-British trade policy announced by the Malaysian government on February
24.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday exports to Malaysia were
Pounds 105m in March compared with Pounds 78m in January and Pounds 102m in
February.
The CSO's figures showed that the total UK visible trade deficit with
countries outside the European Union widened slightly to Pounds 675m in
March from a revised Pounds 640m in February. The consensus forecast was for
a deficit of Pounds 750m.
Excluding oil and erratic items - such as aircraft and precious stones  -
the deficit widened to Pounds 702m from Pounds 683m in February.
Exports to non-EU countries were worth Pounds 5.1bn in March, 2 per cent
below February's level. Imports were Pounds 5.7bn, 1 per cent down on the
previous month.
In the three months to March, exports to non-EU countries increased by 0.5
per cent compared with the previous quarter while imports grew by 2.5 per
cent.
The visible deficit was Pounds 2.1bn in the first quarter, which compares
with a deficit of Pounds 1.8bn in the fourth quarter of 1993.
The main reason for the widening of the deficit in March was a decline in
exports of semi-manufactured goods. In the three months to March import
volumes of semi-manufactured goods rose by 11.0 per cent compared with the
previous three months.
'This is a healthy sign that manufacturing production is set to rise very
strongly' because companies use semi-manufactures to produce finished goods,
said Mr Robert Barrie, UK economist at Barclays de Zoete Wedd.
The CSO said import volumes were showing little growth after revising
downwards its estimate of import volumes and revising upwards its estimate
of import prices. Previously, the CSO had estimated that import volumes were
growing at 1 per cent per month.
Export prices increased by 2 per cent between the fourth quarter of 1993 and
the first quarter of 1994 to a record while import prices rose by 0.5 per
cent.
Mr Adrian Cooper, UK economist at James Capel, said: 'It is clear that
export prices are rising to offset the deterioration in export volumes.'
Between February and March, import volumes excluding oil and erratics rose
by 1 per cent while exports excluding oil and erratics fell by 0.5 per cent.
