<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / PEPs push unit trusts to record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unit trust sales reached a new record of Pounds 1.37bn last month, more than
Pounds 200m above the best previous month, September 1987, when net sales
were Pounds 1.16bn. More unit trusts were sold in March than in January and
February combined.
Strong sales of unit trust Personal Equity Plans were an important factor in
the record sales. PEPs, which shield investments from income and capital
gains tax, accounted for about three-quarters of total net sales to private
investors during the first three months of the year.
By the end of March the total value of all unit trust funds was Pounds
95.5bn, up 35 per cent on the comparable figure for the end of March last
year.
UK equity income funds were the most popular category among private
investors. Overall total net sales of growth funds topped the March list at
Pounds 313m, followed by equity income funds at Pounds 258m, and Pounds 253m
for 'funds of funds' - trusts which invest in other trusts. One of the most
popular income PEPs, M&amp;G's Managed Income PEP, counts as a fund of funds.
Unit trusts aiming to provide a high income have been extremely popular as
interest rates have fallen, particularly among former bank and building
society investors.
PEP sales have provided a significant boost to overall unit trust sales
since the 1992 Budget allowed the whole of a Pounds 6,000 general PEP to be
invested in a suitable unit or investment trust. Sales are normally strong
before the end of the tax year on April 5.
Competition between unit trust groups has tended to focus on the PEP market.
On January 4, M&amp;G added a fresh twist to this competition by removing the
initial charge from its Managed Income PEP. It then sold Pounds 250m-worth
in the first quarter and Pounds 150m-worth in March alone.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
