<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / London Conservatives shun national agenda: Some council
chiefs would not even welcome ministerial visits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the non-descript suburbs of London, there is little doubt that the Tories
can expect a poor result in next week's council elections - but it is far
from clear that Labour and the Liberal Democrats will secure an overwhelming
victory. Mr Ronnie Barden, leader of Tory-controlled Redbridge in north-east
London, admitted the party was under pressure but said: 'People will get
quite a shock when they see how resilient the Conservative vote in London
still is.'
The London poll will be at the centre of attention on election night. After
the last council elections in the capital four years ago, outer London
remained the only big blotch of blue on the electoral map. But high
unemployment in some suburbs, overcrowded classrooms and cuts in services
have put this fortress of Conservative local government under threat.
Small swings against them would see the Tories lose control of Ealing, Brent
and Enfield. The Liberal Democrats are fighting ferociously to win control
of Kingston-upon-Thames from the Tories. In Croydon, with its distinctive
skyscrapers, the Conservative leader admitted that his party would lose
control of the council for the first time if 500 traditional Tory voters
vote Labour.
Mr Barden, like other Tory council leaders, confessed that he had a few
concerns. In London, as everywhere else, the unpopularity of Mr John Major's
government is at the heart of both the Labour and Liberal Democrat
campaigns.
Tory councillors are therefore emphasising that this is not a referendum on
national issues, with some underlining the point by quietly sniping at the
government.
Mr Donald Abbott, Tory leader of Harrow, speaks openly about 'distancing
himself from national policies'. Another council leader privately expresses
relief that Mr Michael Portillo, the leader of the Tories' London campaign,
is not visiting the borough.
Others complain that lower levels of government grant to London boroughs
this year - due to demographic changes - have made it hard to avoid
unpopular cuts in services.
Yet London's Tories betray no signs of panic. They know that the other
parties must win over those who were prepared to vote Conservative in 1990,
at the height of the poll tax debacle, when tens of thousands deserted the
party in the rest of the country.
Mr Leslie Winters, a Tory councillor in Brent, said: 'These people look most
likely to abstain on the day - and that is not good enough for Labour.'
Labour must also counter the 'London effect' - the widespread perception of
Labour councils in the capital as 'loony left'.
In Croydon, Labour's canvassing shows they are picking up 35 per cent of the
total vote, with the Tories a little way behind - helped by the 'moderate'
image of local Labour councillors and by the difficulty the Tories have in
blaming an opposition which has never been in power.
Even in Redbridge, Ms Liz Pearce, the Labour group leader, believes her
party might win the 12 seats needed to take overall control.
But in Brent, where the Tory majority is just six, Labour faces a tough
fight to erase memories of its administration of the late 1980s - industrial
action which left streets unclean and rubbish uncollected has not been
forgotten.
A MORI poll for the council has shown a 60 per cent increase in satisfaction
with services since the Tories came to power. There has also been a cut of
Pounds 112 in this year's Band D level of council tax.
In at least two Tory-held boroughs Labour's challenge is overshadowed by the
Liberal Democrats. This is partly because education - a strong issue for the
third party - is of particular local interest.
In Tory-controlled Harrow, Mr Ralph Bancroft, a Liberal Democrat campaigner,
says canvas returns show his party gaining about half of the votes cast with
the Tories and Labour splitting the rest.
Tory-controlled Kingston-upon-Thames, with one of the best
school-performance records in the country, is also one of the party's top
targets. The borough is surrounded by Liberal Democrat-controlled Richmond,
Sutton and Surrey.
The Liberal Democrat campaign is being fought with all the trade marks of a
marginal by-election. Supporters have converted front rooms into
computerised campaign centres distributing orange posters. As a Tory
campaigner put it: 'You have to wear sunglasses on the Kingston by-pass.'
The party needs to win three wards to take control - but two had huge
Conservative and Labour majorities in 1990.
On the night of May 5, the loss of Kingston would be hard for Tories to
stomach. But the party leadership's embarrassment could be mitigated if it
retained some boroughs.
As a Brent council official put it: 'If I were chairman of the Tory party on
election night and had lost quite a few councils, it would still mean a lot
to say that we'd held Brent.'
</TEXT>
