<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Peers deplore threat to defendants' right to silence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government came under pressure in the House of Lords last night to
provide new safeguards for defendants in criminal cases who continue to
exercise the right to silence when questioned by the police.
Lord Alexander of Weedon, the Conservative peer who is chairman of National
Westminster Bank, joined other leading lawyers in criticising proposals to
permit juries to draw inferences from a defendant's refusal to respond to
police or give evidence in court.
Lord Alexander, who is also chairman of the all-party law reform group
Justice, said the proposed change to the right-to-silence procedure amounted
to a 'charter for unlimited police interrogation'.
The criminal justice and public order bill was given an unopposed second
reading, but the government faces opposition when the right-to-silence
clauses are debated during the committee stage.
Viscount Runciman - the crossbencher who presided over the royal commission
whose majority report opposed any change in the right to silence - said the
bill would lead to an increased risk of wrongful convictions.
He said that if the change was introduced experienced criminals would
continue to remain silent. Trials would take longer, he said, involving
additional costs of between Pounds 36m and Pounds 60m a year.
Lord Runciman said those who believed police malpractice had been eliminated
were not living in the real world.
Support for the bill came from Lord Rawlinson, attorney-general in a former
Tory government, who said it introduced a 'rightful change'.
</TEXT>
