<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / MPs urge R&amp;D incentives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government should reconsider its long-standing opposition to tax
incentives for research and development, the Commons science and technology
committee said yesterday.
The committee called for a 'determined and sustained effort' to reverse the
'disturbing decline' in Britain's R&amp;D spending compared with competitors.
The decline caused particular concern because of recent evidence 'which
suggests that there is a significant payback to the economy as a whole from
increased levels of investment in innovation', the committee said.
In last year's white paper on science and technology the government rejected
calls for R&amp;D tax incentives - partly because of studies in the 1980s which
suggested such incentives were inefficient. The committee cited 'impressive'
new international studies which took the opposite view.
'We believe the time has come for a major re-examination of the case for
fiscal incentives for investment in R&amp;D, both at personal and at company
level,' the committee said. 'Such a review should be conducted openly and
its conclusions should be considered by experts outside the Treasury.'
The MPs were influenced especially by the first extensive study of the
long-term effect of R&amp;D tax credits introduced in the US in 1981. This
study, by Professor Bronwyn Hall of the University of California, Berkeley,
showed that the incentives stimulated companies to spend an extra Dollars
2bn a year on R&amp;D at a cost of about Dollars 1bn in lost tax revenues.
Routes Through Which The Science Base is Translated into Innovative and
Competitive Technology. HMSO. Pounds 19.90.
</TEXT>
