<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / India bans foreign share discounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Indian government has banned foreign companies from buying shares in
their stock-exchange listed Indian subsidiaries at a fraction of market
prices.
The decision follows protests from some Indian companies that multinationals
were gaining unfair advantage by arranging for their affiliates to issue
shares to them on a preferential basis at discounts of up to 90 per cent of
the market price. The Finance Ministry has now ruled that shares issued to a
foreign parent must be priced at a minimum of the average price of the
previous six months.
The ruling indicates that the government is taking serious note of
complaints from some leading industrialists that the economic liberalisation
which has swept India since 1991 has favoured foreign groups at the expense
of Indian companies. These industrialists urged the government to create 'a
level playing field' for Indian industry, including equal treatment in the
capital markets.
The ministry's decision does not signal any desire to hold back further
liberalisation. Rather it is seen in Delhi as a response to a one-off
anomaly.
Foreign companies started making big-discount share issues early last year
after the government relaxed curbs on stock market investment, abolishing
long-standing powers to fix issue prices and permitting free pricing.
Under the liberalised regime, companies were free to allot shares on
preferential terms to any shareholder - as long as they secured approval
from at least 75 per cent of shareholders. Shareholders were happy to grant
approval to multinationals because they judged a multinational which
increased its stake would also probably bring other changes such as new
managers or new technology - and benefit all share-holders.
Indian state-owned financial institutions, which hold the bulk of Indian
shares, set rules for minimum pricing, including a minimum price/earnings
ratio of 15. However, because profits in 1991 and 1992 were depressed by
recession, the formula allowed companies to issue shares to their foreign
parents very cheaply. Colgate Palmolive, the US toiletries group, bought
stock in its affiliate at a 90 per cent discount; Burmah Castrol, the UK oil
group, secured an 89 per cent discount on shares in Castrol India. Several
Indian business families jumped on the bandwagon - persuading their
companies to issue shares to founding families at cheap prices.
Last December the institutions set an additional rule, fixing the minimum
price at the average price for the previous six months. Foreign companies
did not like this change, but did not object since the institutions were
exercising their rights as shareholders - as they might in the US or the UK.
However, the institutions' decision did not apply to every listed company
because they do not always have majority shareholding - some important
foreign-related companies have small institutional holdings and large
numbers of individual shareholders.
The government has stepped into the breach and ordered the Reserve Bank of
India, the central bank, to impose pricing rules on share issues to foreign
shareholders. The government also plans in future to amend the Companies Act
to ban all preferential share issues - whether to foreign or domestic
shareholders.
Among foreign companies affected by the new ruling is Hindustan Lever, the
affiliate of Unilever, the Anglo-Dutch group, which plans three separate
issues of stock to Unilever. Hindustan Lever declined to comment last night.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>INZ  India, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
