<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / Belgian premier emerges as favourite to succeed Delors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, prime minister of Belgium, is emerging as favourite to
succeed Mr Jacques Delors as the next president of the European Commission
following tacit support from France and Germany.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany is expected to raise the name of Mr
Dehaene during talks with Mr John Major at Chequers tomorrow. The meeting is
being billed in Brussels as crucial for the succession, and seen as a test
of Britain's political clout inside the European Union after its recent
retreat on voting rights.
Mr Dehaene has won support from Germany and France at the expense of Mr Ruud
Lubbers, the long-serving Dutch prime minister, senior EU diplomats said.
The move towards Mr Dehaene, an avowed federalist, appears to sink the
chances of Sir Leon Brittan, chief EU trade negotiator and senior British
commissioner.
It could also prove awkward for Mr Major as he struggles to avoid a split
inside the Conservative party over Europe. 'If Kohl wants Dehaene, and the
French are behind him, then Major has no choice but to accept,' said one
senior Brussels official.
Mr Kohl's enthusiasm for Mr Dehaene is said to have grown during the Belgian
presidency of the EU which ended last December. Mr Dehaene helped to wrap up
a deal on the location of a dozen Euro-institutions, including the siting of
the European Monetary Institute, forerunner of the European Central Bank, to
Frankfurt, a high German priority.
President Francois Mitterrand and Mr Kohl are said to have cooled toward Mr
Lubbers, partly because of the Dutch presidency's shaky performance in the
run-up to the Maastricht treaty. However, his chances could revive once he
breaks his self-imposed silence after the Dutch elections, to be held next
month.
By one account, Mr Dehaene's candidacy was floated as a Franco-German trial
balloon to undermine the widely held assumption that there was no credible
alternative to Mr Lubbers.
The leak followed talks between Mr Kohl and Mr Edouard Balladur, French
prime minister, but did not come with Mr Dehaene's foreknowledge. He has
since refused all comment on whether he is a candidate.
The post of president of the Commission is decided by the 12 EU heads of
government. They could select a successor at the European summit in Corfu in
June, if they reach the required unanimity.
The Commission presidency is the top prize in a complex division of
Euro-spoils under negotiation. Germany is expected to win the key post of
secretary-general of the European Council, with the appointment of Mr Jurgen
Trumpf, a senior career diplomat.
Britain could, however, win a consolation prize if Lord Lawson - the former
chancellor of the exchequer - is offered German support for his effort to
become the next secretary-general of the Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development.
MEPs seek to tear down curtain of secrecy, Page 2
</TEXT>
