<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 94 / GDP climbs back to pre-recession peak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The UK economy passed another milestone on the recovery trail in the first
quarter of 1994, with gross domestic product finally reclaiming its
pre-recession peak of nearly four years ago.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday that first-quarter GDP, at
constant prices, was 0.7 per cent higher than in the fourth quarter of last
year, and 2.6 per cent above its level in the first quarter of 1993. The
rise keeps the economy well on target for the government's forecast of 2.5
per cent full-year growth.
The figures, which were in line with expectations, were seen by analysts as
evidence that the government would see no need to cut interest rates in the
near term. 'I think there is no chance of a move until after the European
elections,' said Mr Ian Shepherdson, UK economist at Midland Global Markets.
Some analysts, however, expect the tax increases, which took effect this
month, to slow the pace of recovery. Ms Ruth Lea of Lehman Brothers is
forecasting 2 1/4 per cent growth for the whole of 1994.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said in Washington yesterday that his
ambition was to deliver a recovery with lasting low inflation. However, he
admitted that it would take some time for economic improvements to be
appreciated by 'the ordinary Joe in the street'. Mr Clarke also said that a
lower-than-expected public sector borrowing requirement, announced last
week, would not lead the government to be soft on public spending or to make
rapid tax cuts.
First-quarter GDP, in real terms, climbed back to its level in the second
quarter of 1990, having risen by about 4 per cent since its trough in 1992.
A good part of this rebound, however, was due to a surge in North Sea oil
and gas production. If oil and gas are excluded, GDP grew by 0.6 per cent in
the first quarter, and was 2 per cent higher than in the first quarter of
1993. Non-oil GDP is still below its 1990 peak.
Services have contributed more than manufacturing to the recovery. While
service sector output is now 2 per cent ahead of the levels reached in 1990,
manufacturing sector output is still 4-5 per cent below its peak.
The CSO said preliminary figures for the first quarter showed that growth
was fairly widespread. There were signs of strengthening growth in the
construction sector, and of buoyant conditions in the retail, wholesale,
hotels and catering sectors.
Other statistics published yesterday showed the visible trade deficit with
non-European Union countries widened to Pounds 675m in March, from Pounds
640m in February. For the first quarter, the deficit was Pounds 2.12bn,
against Pounds 1.77bn in the fourth quarter of 1993.
Clarke tough on spending, Page 9
Exports to Malaysia rise, Page 10
Lex, Page 22
London stocks, Page 44
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
