<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Company news (This week): Progress comes into sight after
the clear-out - Sears
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The improvement in the performance of Sears, the UK's largest multiple high
street retailer, over the past two years has been obscured by a mass of
restructuring charges. But tomorrow it is expected to give a clear message
with an increase in full-year pre-tax profits to about Pounds 127m.
That represents a substantial uplift from last year's Pounds 83.5m after a
net Pounds 16.9m of exceptional costs. The increase is even more dramatic on
an FRS 3 basis, according to which Sears made a prior-year loss of Pounds
47.8m, after Pounds 106.8m of charges.
The advance reflects the success of Mr Liam Strong, chief executive since
February 1992, in refocusing the sprawling retail group. He has shaken up
senior management, established a clear strategy and sold non-core
businesses.
The first stage was the reorganisation of British Shoe Corporation, the UK's
largest footwear retailer, then operating under five fascias including
Dolcis, Saxone and Freeman Hardy Willis. Mr Strong closed 350 shops, cutting
1,800 jobs, as well as introducing the mass market format Shoe Express, the
more middle market Hush Puppy, and out-of-town Shoe City.
The challenge for Sears now is to improve the performance of its other
retail businesses: in womenswear and childrenswear - which include names
such as Wallis, Miss Selfridge and Richards; sport and leisure (Olympus,
Milletts); and mail order (Freemans).
The uplift in profits suggests Mr Strong is having some success. However,
the performance of the Adams childrenswear chain remains a concern, with
rival Mothercare, staging a recovery. The future of the mail order business,
number four in the UK, is also open to debate.
As for Selfridges, the prestigious Oxford Street department store, Sears has
demonstrated its commitment by announcing a Pounds 50m update.
</TEXT>
