<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Bosnian talks resume as Serbs pull back weapons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM, LAURA SILBER and BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Talks on reviving peace efforts in Bosnia will be held today in London
involving the US, Britain, France and Russia following the Serbs' removal of
weapons from the centre of Gorazde under threat of massive air strikes.
General Sir Michael Rose, United Nations commander in Bosnia, said yesterday
the Serbs had pulled their heavy armour out of a 3km exclusion zone,
bringing some relief to the besieged town.
The Serbs, defying international condemnation, have established a
stranglehold on Gorazde in an offensive that began at the end of last month.
More than 700 people have died in the 65,000-strong enclave, one of six
so-called Bosnian safe havens the UN has pledged to protect.
Gen Rose said the Serbs were also beginning to move equipment out of a
broader 20km zone which Nato has told them to evacuate by tomorrow night.
Nato and UN officials also claimed to have patched up a row that flared on
Saturday after the UN turned down a proposal from the alliance to launch an
air attack against the Serbs.
Yesterday's lull enabled the UN to begin evacuating the wounded. UK and
French helicopters began transporting more than 600 seriously injured people
to Sarajevo. A convoy of 14 UN food trucks arrived in Gorazde last night,
the first supplies since March 28.
Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of state, said Nato demands for an
end to shelling in Gorazde and a partial withdrawal of Serb forces had
apparently been heeded. Bosnia's Moslem-led government insisted that some
artillery fire was continuing.
Mr Christopher said Gorazde had seen only small arms fire yesterday. 'The
withdrawal was somewhat spotty, but my latest reports from the scene are
that the withdrawal is taking place,' he said in a television interview.
He is due in London today for talks with Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary, and Mr Alain Juppe, foreign minister of France. Mr Vitaly
Churkin, Russia's chief negotiator on former Yugoslavia, is expected to meet
British diplomats separately.
Mr Haris Silajdzic, Bosnian prime minister, said Gorazde was still a scene
of fighting, as Bosnian radio reported artillery and sniper attacks. In
Zagreb, Mr Yasushi Akashi, the senior UN official in former Yugoslavia, said
observers could no longer see any heavy weapons inside the exclusion belt
around Gorazde.
The zone was a main Nato demand last week when it threatened wider use of
air power. US officials confirmed they had backed Nato's request  - denied
by the UN  - to begin strikes on Saturday when the Serbs failed to stop
shelling, and had since made progress in gaining UN support for use of air
power.
Nato tries to play down Bosnia row, Page 3
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
    HRZ  Croatia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
