<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Observer in South Africa: And now, the news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the bad old days, the South African Broadcasting Corporation was utterly
under the thumb of the ruling National party. Fortunately, the ANC is
committed to an independent state broadcasting system.
So the top three posts in the new SABC hierarchy are all occupied by ANC
supporters, including Zwelakhe Sisulu, former editor of the pro-ANC
newspaper The New Nation. Walter Sisulu, once of the most senior executive
members of the party, is his dad.
Maybe they should pin on the office walls some lines from William Blake:
The iron hand crushed the tyrant's head,
And became a tyrant in his stead.
