<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It has come to a pretty pass when about the only thing in which we lead the
world is the sleaziness of our tabloid press. The Hunt for Michael Jackson
(BBC 2, 9pm) is an attempt by US television to dish the dirt on the
beleagured pop star. It leans on the expertise of British journos buying
into the confidences of Jackson's disaffected entourage. The programme has
it both ways: pedalling gossip while throwing up its hands in horror at such
mercenary goings on.
The BBC's attempts to repair its audience share by screening a third episode
of EastEnders was undermined by ITV extending Coronation Street to a full
hour. Tonight Rowan Atkinson's Mind The Baby, Mr Bean is fielded at 8pm in
an attempt to destroy the BBC soap.
Why can't the UK produce a decent tennis player? Not for lack of money. Much
of the profits from Wimbledon go into training young hopefuls and Champions:
Hothouse Tennis (Channel 4, 9pm) takes us to the Lawn Tennis Association's
school at Bisham Abbey - but offers little hope.
