<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Pounds 11bn Lloyd's gap feared: Reserves warning as action
by 3,000 hard-hit Names begins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's of London could have a shortfall of at least Pounds 11bn in its
reserves set aside for future US asbestosis and pollution claims, a report
to be published today warns.
The report estimates the insurance market's total liabilities from US
asbestosis and pollution at Pounds 15bn against reserves to meet those
claims of about Pounds 4bn.
'Policyholders will be dismayed to learn of the modest scale of financial
resources that Lloyd's has available to meet legitimate claims,' says the
report, prepared by a team headed by US lawyer Mr Randolph Fields as part of
a research programme under the auspices of the financial services department
at London Guildhall University.
Lloyd's Names, the individuals whose assets support the market, have already
lost more than Pounds 7bn in the past five years and will be faced with huge
extra calls on their funds, the report says.
The biggest legal action by loss-making Names begins tomorrow, when a case
brought by 3,095 members of syndicates formerly managed by the Gooda Walker
agency comes to court. Lloyd's remains confident of success for its plans to
set up a new reinsurance company into which most of its asbestosis and
pollution liabilities will be transferred.
Mr Peter Middleton, the market's chief executive, said in Lloyd's annual
report, also published today, that the company  - to be known as NewCo  -
will be set up by the end of 1995, offering Names 'an exit route from
Lloyd's in respect of their pre-1986 liabilities'.
However the report, which is partially based on figures from about
three-quarters of Lloyd's syndicates, suggests that these efforts could come
to grief because of the way reserves have been treated.
It had been expected that Lloyd's would seek to raise funds to capitalise
NewCo by discounting an estimated Pounds 4bn in reserves held in its premium
trust funds  - money set aside to meet future claims. Discounting is a
common practice in the insurance industry which allows insurers to take into
account investment income earned on reserves for claims which may emerge
many years hence.
The report, however, claims that as much as Pounds 2.8bn of the Pounds 4bn
reserves is in the form of financial reinsurance due to the widespread use
by many syndicates at Lloyd's of time and distance policies  - a reinsurance
similar to an investment contract. In these policies a premium is paid to a
reinsurer in return for the guaranteed return of the premium and a future
investment income at a fixed future date.
'Thousands of Names will each be faced with meeting cash calls of up to
hundreds of thousands of pounds to replace what is in effect the 'bad' money
of time and distance policies with more of their own good money,' the report
says.
The study adds that the degree of under-reserving for old years' claims
relating to asbestos and pollution claim liabilities is 'astounding', even
taking into account what it calls a 'conservative' approach to estimating
liabilities.
Lloyd's began its own detailed work on assessing its liabilities and assets
in relation to old years last year as part of its plans to establish NewCo.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Lloyd's of London.
    NewCo.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
