<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / First shares to be issued under BES successor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tax breaks for investors introduced in last year's November Budget are to be
exploited for the first time - by a shipping company.
Altnamara Shipping is believed to be the first company to plan an issue of
shares under the Enterprise Investment Scheme, designed as a replacement for
the defunct Business Expansion Scheme.
The BES, introduced in 1983, was abolished at the end of last year after the
Treasury lost patience with the way that tax incentives intended to
encourage investment in high-risk start-up businesses were instead being
applied to rental property schemes guaranteed by banks.
BES loan-back schemes, which allowed investors in effect to withdraw their
money after six months, rather than the usual five-year qualifying period,
while still benefiting from the tax relief, were abolished by the Budget in
March last year.
The rules for the new enterprise scheme have been tightened up to exclude
low-risk property schemes and limit the tax breaks to genuine trading
companies. Investors are locked in for at least five years.
Tax incentives under the enterprise scheme are less generous initially, but
geared towards making the risk more palatable.
The BES offered up-front tax relief of up to 40 per cent on investments of
Pounds 40,000 a year, but no relief on losses, while the new scheme limits
up-front relief to 20 per cent. But the annual allowance has been raised to
Pounds 100,000, and losses can be offset against income or capital gains
tax.
Altnamara Shipping, which describes itself as Scottish-based, intends to
purchase and operate a second-hand dry bulk carrier. The company was set up
last year with capital of Pounds 420,000 raised under the BES.
It is now seeking up to Pounds 4.7m with a share issue that qualifies under
the enterprise scheme.
Most companies will normally be able to raise a maximum of Pounds 1m a year
through the scheme, but shipping companies have a limit of Pounds 5m.
The scheme appears in the finance bill, which has not yet become law, and no
new shares in Altnamara will be issued until the bill has received the royal
assent.
</TEXT>
