<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Pay shows sign of rising trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Signs that pay is starting to climb during the recovery appear in earnings
surveys published today. They show that the trend of decreasing salary rises
for managers appears to have ended and may already have been reversed.
Managers' pay did not rise as much last year as in 1992, but remained well
ahead of inflation and pay rises for other employees. Managers' earnings
rose 4.5 per cent in the year to January, the fourth successive year in
which they have recorded smaller increases than the previous year, says the
Institute of Management's annual survey of more than 20,000 managers. It
says directors' pay rises fell back slightly from 6.5 per cent to 6.1 per
cent last year.
The value of managers' and director's bonuses, measured as a percentage of
earnings, has increased in the past year to 13.9 per cent although it
remains below the 1988 level of 16.3 per cent.
The gross earnings of managers, including allowances, rose 2 per cent last
year and directors took home more than 3 per cent extra. But their earnings
would have to leap by at least 7 per cent in the coming year to avoid any
cut in take-home pay resulting from this month's rises in tax and National
Insurance contributions.
Other indications of an upturn in the rate of executive salary increases
have emerged in a report by Sedgwick Noble Lowndes, the pay and benefit
consultants. It records a marginal rise in the median base salary award.
'This is the first indication we have seen for several years of a rise in
executive pay awards,' said Mr Andy Christie, the company's remuneration
consulting director. 'It is too early to predict an upward swing in 1994,
but we believe the figures may be evidence at least of an end to the
downward trend that began four years ago.'
The reports of management pay increases coincide with a series of
above-inflation wage agreements recorded by Incomes Data Services, the pay
analyst, in a report published today.
Burton Group has awarded 32,300 retail staff and managers merit rises of up
to 5 per cent and has switched staff in 18 stores to higher pay grades in
response to labour market pressures.
Mr Roger Young, director of the Institute of Management, urged managers and
directors not to complain too loudly about this month' higher taxes. He
said: 'Managers and directors are still receiving better pay rises than the
rest of the workforce.' They might think the percentage is small, but when
compared to those who have had to take a pay freeze or who have lost their
jobs, they have done very well.'
Institute of Management National Management Salary Survey, Remuneration
Economics, Survey House, 51 Portland Road, Kingston-upon-Thames, Surrey KT1
2SH, Pounds 360.
IDS Report 663, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS.
Sedgwick Noble Lowndes Management Compensation Database. 081 666 8478.
