<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Scrap employment ministry, say engineers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Engineering Employers Feder-ation, one of Britain's largest employers'
organisations, is calling for the Department of Employment to be broken up
and its functions shared between the Department of Trade and Industry and
Department for Education.
With the debate about its future gathering in intensity, the employment
ministry appears to have surprisingly few friends. But it still has enough
institutional clout to ensure that most of its critics advocate
dismemberment in private.
Mrs Anne Minto, director of policy at the federation, has no such
inhibitions. She says the department's training functions should be
transferred to the education department. Many other critics of the
employment department  - which include the Commons trade and industry
committee in a report to be published this week  - would prefer training to
go to the DTI because the education department is seen as unsympathetic to
vocational education.
'Experience with the Department for Education has not been that favourable
from an employers' point of view,' said an official from a rival employers'
body, who also thinks the Department of Employment looks more vulnerable
than it has for many years.
Some observers question the assumption that the merging of income support
and unemployment benefit into the Jobseekers' Allowance will help the
employment department even if the government decides that payment of the
allowance should rest with that department rather than the Department of
Social Security.
Ms Pam Meadows, head of the Policy Studies Institute and a former chief
economist in the Department of Employment, says: 'The Jobseekers' Allowance
is certainly about moving benefit away from welfare and linking it more to
the labour market, but that merely means that there is a strong case for the
Employment Service agency to report to an economic department.'
Critics say many functions which used to justify the existence of a separate
Department of Employment have been subcontracted to agencies. Training is
dealt with by the Tecs, industrial relations by Acas, health and safety by
the Health and Safety Commission, and unemployment benefit and job placement
by the Employment Service.
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, gives the
employment department only two cheers even though its abolition would curb
his chance of influence in Whitehall.
'The department in recent years has fallen far short of promoting full
employment,' he said. 'But the DTI's poor record on promoting industrial
development does not inspire confidence that it would promote training more
effectively than the (employment department).'
</TEXT>
