<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Defiant PM vows to see job through
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday shrugged off the latest bout of Conservative
speculation about his leadership, insisting that he would not be forced out
of Downing Street by poor results in the local and European elections. 'I
have got things I wish to do, and I am going to go on doing them,' Mr Major
said. 'I will go when people least expect it. But I have got a lot to do
yet.'
Mr Major's defiant stand, in an interview with the German magazine Der
Spiegel, followed a renewed outbreak of leadership manoeuvring by supporters
of Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, and of Mr Michael
Portillo, Treasury chief secretary.
Friends of Mr Portillo said he was attracting increased support following an
appeal last week for Conservatives to heed the concerns of the 'quiet
majority'.
However, few MPs think that Mr Portillo could win a leadership battle
against Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, or Mr Heseltine.
Supporters of Mr Major appeared more concerned about the threat from Mr
Heseltine, who has emerged as favourite to win if a leadership election is
held later this year.
Sir Archibald Hamilton, a former defence minister, appealed to Mr Heseltine
to stop his supporters openly canvassing Conservative MPs.
He said: 'If Michael Heseltine has not, as he says, claims to the
leadership, I think it would be a very good idea if he told those that are
working for him that this was the position and would they back off.'
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, said reports of leadership
manoeuvring were 'nonsense'. Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, said
speculation was 'unreal'.
Speaking on BBC radio, Mr Hurd said: 'The prime minister is a man of steel.
He is going to go on, and people are going to want him to go on.'
The government's election difficulties may be compounded this week by a row
over potential cuts to the armed forces coinciding with the release of the
annual defence white paper.
The paper is expected to attempt to minimise the impact of defence cuts on
the local elections on May 5 and the European elections on June 9.
But ministers are close to approving sweeping cuts identified by more than
30 defence working parties set up last year by Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence
minister.
The cuts, which will include civilian redundancies, property sales, vehicle
leasing and a reduction in the number of senior officers, are expected to be
announced in June after the European elections.
</TEXT>
