<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Former Tory flagship fires warning shot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The defeat of the Conservative candidates in the last two parliamentary
by-elections at Newbury and Christchurch was enough for Mrs Margaret
Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, to reach for the champagne, irrespective of
her party's poor third place.
If the pattern is repeated in Eastleigh, there will be no such celebration
for Labour. For once, the interest in the Hampshire by-election is as much
about who comes second as who wins.
The by-election, expected on June 9, was called after the death in February
of the Conservative MP Stephen Milligan.
Reading their election literature, Eastleigh's constituents could be
forgiven for forgetting that the Conservatives are defending what was once
regarded as a safe seat. Labour and the Liberal Democrats are running their
campaigns on the assumption that the Conservative vote has already
collapsed.
For a constituency which had a 17,702 Tory majority at the last general
election, that appears to be a big assumption. But there is ample evidence
to suggest that the two main opposition parties are not indulging in wishful
thinking.
From the plush northern suburbs around Chandler's Ford, known locally as
'gin and Jaguar' territory, to the southern opulence of the marina in
Hamble-le-Rice, it is surprisingly difficult to find anyone who admits to be
planning to vote Conservative.
Mr John Major may shrug off a defeat in Eastleigh as a typical bout of
mid-term blues  - the familiar story of the loss of a safe seat in a
by-election which returns to the Tory fold at the next general election.
But if the Conservative candidate, Mr Stephen Reid, can no longer rely on
the goodwill, let alone the loyalty, of the regulars in Hamble's pubs and
clubs, then the prime minister should know that something is seriously
wrong.
The mere mention of 'the C word' at Hamble's King and Queen public house,
which subscribes to Yachting Monthly, is enough to ignite a storm of
protest.
Lifelong Tories fume about the government's 'treachery over taxation',
complain that there are few signs of recovery, express anger at the
imposition of value added tax on domestic fuel and laugh in dismay at the
recent row over qualified majority voting in Europe.
Almost all defecting Tories say they will vote Liberal Democrat, though with
little enthusiasm for, or understanding of what the party stands for.
The Liberal Democrats came second in the last three general elections in
Eastleigh and out-polled Labour in the recent county and borough elections,
but the Labour candidate, Mrs Marilyn Birks, is fighting for every vote.
Even the Liberal Democrats would not deny that there is a core Labour vote
in parts of the constituency. It is mostly concentrated in the Woolston
ward, which is in Southampton.
But the northern part of the constituency tells a different story. Many
workers from the British Rail maintenance works  - which gave Eastleigh its
reputation as a railway town  - are more determined to give the government
'a bloody nose' than to vote positively for one of the opposition parties.
In the Comrades and Unity working men's clubs there is talk of voting for
the Liberal Democrats as the best-placed party to take the seat.
In spite of the recent visit of members of the shadow cabinet to the Unity
Club, Mr Ray Chapman, a 21-year-old mechanical worker, strikes a chord with
many of his friends when he says he will vote Liberal Democrat 'because they
are the best lot to get the Tories out'.
Try as Labour does to focus the campaign on the Liberal Democrat's record on
the county council  - alleging incompetence and waste and criticising them
for environmental problems surrounding the airport  - there is no evidence
that people are more interested in local issues. The by-election is seen as
a referendum on Mr Major's government.
Mr David Chidgey, the Liberal Democrat candidate, stands to be the main
beneficiary of such a contest. He accuses Mrs Beckett of keeping the
'vintage champagne' on ice in case the Tories make a late recovery.
Notwithstanding the campaigning talents of Mrs Birks, Labour is unlikely to
have much to celebrate from the Eastleigh result.
</TEXT>
<XX>
