<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 94 / Doubt cast on Heseltine's effectiveness
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When Mr Bill Cockburn, Post Office chief executive, voiced his frustration
last week over the government's failure to decide whether to privatise his
organisation, he was echoing wider feelings about the Department of Trade
and Industry.
The 21-month delay in his case is among the longest for a stalled DTI
initiative. But several other important measures have been pending for long
enough to cause uncertainty and raise questions about the effectiveness of
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary.
Some of the delay is deliberate: the government is anxious to avoid
controversial announcements before the local and European elections, and
orders have gone out to hold fire where possible. But some of it seems to
have been caused by departmental wrangling.
Mr Heseltine is committed to privatising Royal Mail. He favours selling its
letters and parcels divisions, leaving the counters division  - responsible
for post offices  - in the public sector.
But powerful voices, such as Lord Wakeham, leader of the House of Lords, Mr
Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons,
and Mr Richard Ryder, chief whip, strongly oppose Post Office privatisation.
A senior Whitehall official said Mr Heseltine was prepared to compromise by
advocating the flotation of a minority stake of Royal Mail and parcels if
that would win over ministers opposed to the privatisation. The issue is
expected to be debated in cabinet shortly.
In the case of the gas industry, Mr Heseltine announced an end to British
Gas's monopoly in December, promising a consultation document on a new
market structure early this year. Ofgas, the industry regulator, prepared
detailed proposals and passed them to the DTI.
Several months later, there is still no sign of this document, and the gas
industry is becoming anxious. The Society of British Gas Industries, which
wrote to Mr Heseltine last week seeking clarification, said it was 'very
concerned if the government is now going to say that the date they gave last
year is no longer effective'.
Industry executives say important investment decisions have been put on
hold. There is even concern that de-regulation will not occur before the
next election, in which case it may not occur at all.
The speculation in gas circles is that Mr Heseltine is beginning to dislike
the idea of gas de-regulation, and that the Ofgas proposals were not
acceptable to him. The consultation document will be largely technical, but
could affect the availability and price of gas in the domestic market. It
could also give ammunition to the opposition. So action may be held up until
after the elect-ions.
A review of the nuclear power industry was first promised 13 months ago as
part of the settlement of the coal crisis. It has been repeatedly postponed,
most recently at the end of March only hours before the chairmen of the
nuclear companies were due to meet Mr Heseltine.
At first the DTI blamed the delay on legal challenges to its decision to
approve the operation of Thorp, the nuclear reprocessing facility in
Cumbria. A further complication has arisen over authorisations for the new
nuclear power station at Sizewell. Above this is departmental in-fighting
over the review's terms of reference.
The state-owned nuclear power industry is keen to have the review because it
could pave the way to privatisation. But as delays drag on, some nuclear
executives suspect the review could be cancelled as too controversial.
Whitehall officials blame the delay in the nuclear review on the protracted
struggle between the Treasury and the DTI over whether the industry can be
privatised. Unlike the Post Office, Mr Heseltine is strongly opposed to a
sale, believing it to be practically and politically unworkable.
The DTI also strongly rebuts the Treasury's argument that privatisation of
the nuclear industry would not need primary legislation since it was
provided for in electricity privatisation.
One DTI official said: 'We do not believe that is an accurate reading of the
original documents. Any attempt to move the nuclear industry into the
private sector without a vote in parliament may lead to a challenge in
court.'
</TEXT>
