 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Northern Transvaal         Eastern Transvaal         Pretoria/Witwater-
                                                     srand/Vereeniging
                                                     (PWV)
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
African     95.5%          African     86.7%         African     62.3%
White        4.2%          White       12.2%         White       32.1%
Indian       0.1%          Indian       0.5%         Indian       2.1%
Coloured     0.2%          Coloured     0.6%         Coloured     3.4%
Voters      2.29m          Voters      1.59m         Voters      4.86m
Percentage of              Percentage of             Percentage of
total voting               total voting              total voting
population   10.1          population    7.0         population   21.4
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
EACH VOTER HAS TWO VOTES
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
 -Parliament will have two houses: a 400-seat National Assembly, elected
  by the people, and a 90-seat Senate, with ten members elected
  indirectly by each of the nine provincial legislatures.
 -The voter votes twice, once for a single party or organisation on the
  national lists and once for a single party or organisation on the
  provincial lists.
 -National Assembly seats are then allocated by proportional
  representation, 200 from national lists and 200 from provincial lists,
  except in the case of the National Party, which has no national list
  and will choose all its representatives from provincial lists.
 -Provincial legislatures will range from 30 to 86 members, seats
  allocated by proportional representation.
 -National cabinet posts will be allocated proportionately from parties
  holding a minimum of 20 seats.
 -The president will be elected by a joint session of both houses.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
THE MAIN CONTENDERS
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
African National Congress
Leader: Nelson Mandela
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Founded 1912, banned in 1960 until February 1990, and at the forefront
of the struggle against apartheid, the ANC is the leader of the
'tripartite alliance' with the Congress of South African Trade Unions
(Cosatu) and the South African Communist Party (see below). Its
Reconstruction and Development Programme promises to redress the legacy
of apartheid.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
National Party
Leader: FW de Klerk
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Orginally exlusively Afrikaner, now includes much coloured, Indian and
some black support. Party founded in 1914 and came to power in 1948
advocating racial separation. Concept of apartheid and black homelands
refined in 1960s. 'New' party has apologised for its past. Asserts
Christian and familiy values, national reconciliation and strong
economic growth.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Inkatha Freedom Party
Leader: Mangosuthu Buthelezi
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Formed in 1975 as a Zulu cultural organisation, with the blessing of
ANC, but the two groups fell out in late 1970s, partly due to
Buthelezi's opposition to sanctions and the ANC military campaign.
Thousands have died in clashes between rival supporters since 1984.
Stands for greater power to Natal, home to most of country's 9m Zulus.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Freedom Front
Leader: Constand Viljeon
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
A group of retired army officers last year formed the Afrikaner
Volksfront (People's Front) to unify the Afrikaner right and resist
transition. Last month, Gen Viljoen, the movement's leader, broke away
to form a new group, the Freedom Front (VF/FF), to contest the
elections, using them as a referendum to test support for an Afrikaner
volkstaat (homeland).
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Communist Party
Leader: Joe Slovo
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Allied with the ANC, the party's members fill many top spots on the ANC
election list. Chairman Slovo has tried hard to lay to rest the
'communist bogey' and emphasises the party has no 'hidden agenda'. But
many South Africans remain hostile to the party, and many Christian
voters reject the ANC because of its communist connections.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Democratic Party
Leader: Zach de Beer
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Founded 1989, its historical roots are in the now defunct Progressive
Federal Party, in turn formed in 1959 by a group of liberal white
members of parliament, including Helen Suzman. Strong civil rights
platform. Advocates clean government, deregulation and law and order.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Pan Africanist Congress
Leader: Clarence Makwetu
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Founded in 1959 when an 'Africanist' faction left ANC and now advocates
radical economic reform, stressing redistribution of land. Support in
Cape and PWV regions and township youth. Armed wing, the Azanian
People's Liberation Army (APLA), attacked white targets in 1993 but
announced moratorium this year.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
THE BOYCOTTERS
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Conservative Party
Leader: Ferdie Hartzenberg
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Founded 1982 to seek to enforce apartheid, now wants a volkstaat. The
KP/CP won 31 per cent of vote in the last all-white election in 1989 and
advocated a No vote in 1993 referendum, in which 35.5 per cent opposed
reform. But subsequent splits in the country's right wing make the
party's strength hard to assess.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
